AB  -      Lean mass is positively associated with bone mineral density (BMD). However, the relationship between adiposity and BMD is controversial. It is unclear if the observational association reflects a causal effect of fat mass on BMD. Mendelian randomization (MR) studies using variants in the FTO and MC4R as genetic instruments for adiposity have suggested that fat mass causally influence BMD. However, it is possible that these genetic variants pleiotropically influence lean mass and affect BMD through pathways independent of adiposity, invalidating a core assumptions of MR. To investigate whether adiposity causally affects BMD, we examined the relationship between fat mass and BMD [at the skull(SK),upper-(UL)andlower-limbs(LL)]in5221ALSPACchildren using body mass index (BMI) associated SNPs, including a variant near ADCY3 that was associated with fat but not lean mass. Conventional MR analyses were performed in addition to new extensions of the MR method: MR Egger regression and multivariable MR which are more robusttopossible confoundingeffects duetohorizontalpleiotropy, andin the case of multivariable MR, account for the effect of lean mass. Observationally, fat mass was positively related to BMD at all sites, but more weakly at the skull. IV analyses suggested that fat mass was causally related to limb BMD, but not SK-BMD. Multivariable MR, Egger regression and IV analyses involving the ADCY3 variant suggested a positive causal effect of adiposity on all sites except the skull and that an effect was present after taking lean mass into account. Reciprocal IV analyses showed no evidence of reverse causality. Our results suggest that adiposity is causally related to increased BMD at all sites except the skull, perhaps reflecting positive effects of loading on bone formation. Our results illustrate how MR can be used profitably to investigate clinical questions relevant to osteoporosis. Medical Research Council program Grant (MC-UU-12013/4). The UK Medical Research Council and the Wellcome Trust (Grant Refs: 092731 and 102215/2/13/2).
