AB  -      Background: A higher body mass index (BMI) is known to be associated with lower 25-hydroxyvitamin D concentrations [25(OH)D, an indicator for vitamin D status], although the direction of the relationship has not been proven. The aim of the study was to explore the causal direction of the relationship between obesity and vitamin D deficiency using a bidirectional Mendelian randomization (MR) approach. Methods: We used 12 BMIrelated SNPs and 4 vitamin D-related SNPs individually and in combination as instruments in the analyses on ~40,000 individuals from 21 studies. Results: In meta-analysis, each 10 unit increase in BMI was associated with 12% reduction in 25(OH)D. BMI score and the two vitamin D allele counts (formed separately for synthesis and metabolism SNPs) showed the expected strong associations with lnBMI and ln25(OH)D, respectively (p<0.0001 for three comparisons), with no evidence for heterogeneity by region, age, gender and assay suggesting these scores as valid instruments for MR analyses. The continuous BMI score was also associated with a decrease in ln25(OH)D [beta(95%CI)= -0.06(-0.10, -0.02), p= 0.003], while no association was seen between either vitamin D allele counts and lnBMI (synthesis allele count, p= 0.85; metabolism allele count, p= 0.09). In the instrumental variable analyses, we found a significant causal association of BMI score with ln25(OH)D [beta(95%CI)= -0.38(-0.64, -0.11), p= 0.005]. Conclusions: In conclusion, using a bidirectional genetic approach that limits confounding, our data suggests that increases in BMI lead to vitamin D deficiency, while evidence did not suggest that improvements in vitamin D status could contribute to reductions in BMI.
