AB  -      Introduction: Obesity is consistently implicated in the pathogenesis of obstructive sleep apnoea (OSA). A common single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) of the fat mass and obesity-associated (FTO) gene(rs9939609) is strongly associated with body mass index (BMI). Caucasian adults homozygous for the minor (A) allele were 3-4 kg heavier and demonstrated a 1.7-fold increase in the odds of obesity compared to those without the AA genotype1. We aimed to determine whether FTO genotype is associated with either the presence or severity of OSA and to explore the potential causal relationship between BMI and OSA severity. Methods: OSA cases comprised European subjects from the WA Sleep Health Study who had polysomnography-defined OSA (Apnoea Hypopnea Index; AHI >= 5). Controls comprised European participants from the 1994-95 Busselton Health Study who were screened using questionnaire data for the probable absence of moderate to severe OSA.Cases and controls were genotyped for FTO (rs9939609). AHI was used to define OSA severity. The role of the FTO SNP in the presence of andseverity of OSA were investigated using multivariate analyses of AHI, age, BMI and FTO genotype. Mendelian Randomisation (MR) analysis utilises the random assignment of a genotype to make causal inferences about environmental risk factors for disease outcomes. In this study the FTO SNP (rs9939609) will be used as an instrumental variable for BMI to assess the relationship between BMI and AHI. Results: There were 1240 cases and 1955 controls. FTO was not associated with either the presence or severity of OSA. BMI adjusted for age and sex was significantly associated with Loge(AHI) (P < 0.001) explaining22% of the variance. Within OSA patients the FTO genotype was associated with BMI (P = 0.01). These traditional epidemiological associations suggest that FTO may be a suitable instrument variable for investigating the relationship between BMI and AHI. Discussion: The FTO gene had no association with OSA susceptibilityor severity. Multivariate associations suggest that BMI impacts severityof OSA however the association does not imply causation. Analyses using Mendelian randomisation techniques will be presented which may further elucidate the relationship between OSA and obesity.
